		<item>
		<title>Helping hires excel</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2013/03/helping-hires-excel/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2013/03/helping-hires-excel/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 12 Mar 2013 12:00:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[advice]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[hiring]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[management]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[training]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=931</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>A little bit of training and discipline when a new employee starts can go a long way to making their tenure with you a success. Not enough attention or investment is paid to training new employees. Well-orchestrated and properly designed &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/03/helping-hires-excel/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/03/helping-hires-excel/">Helping hires excel</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Helping Hires Excel" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/HelpingHiresExcel.jpg" alt="Helping Hires Excel" /></p>
<figcaption>A little bit of training and discipline when a new employee starts can go a long way to making their tenure with you a success.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Not enough attention or investment is paid to training new employees. Well-orchestrated and properly designed training is proven to increase retention. More than that, it creates alignment between the new hire and the expectations of the company, management and their particular position. It also is the best time to get an employee&#8217;s behaviour to shift from their past or natural inclinations into what your organization needs.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ve all heard the phrase &#8220;honeymoon phase&#8221;. This is the period when a person &#8211; whether in a new job or new relationship &#8211; is behaving aspirationally and trying to adapt to better fit with their opposite. Not only is it the time when you see more of the &#8220;best self&#8221; of a person, it is when they are most susceptible to training and change.</p>
<p>You have a short period of time after a new employee comes to teach them new things that require big behavior change and make it stick. Even if someone doesn&#8217;t like process &#8211; say, using Salesforce.com to track their sales activity &#8211; you can often get them on board and using it if you get them on it early and turn it into a habit. On the other hand, when you have an employee who has been working at your company without that discipline for a long time and then you try to get them on it, it is much harder.</p>
<p>Being sure to train new employees just makes sense. We invest our time and money in finding and closing new talent; shouldn&#8217;t we do our best to make their tenure as long and productive as possible? It&#8217;s a no brainer.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/03/helping-hires-excel/">Helping hires excel</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
