		<item>
		<title>The Final Cut</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/the-final-cut/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/the-final-cut/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 08 Jan 2013 17:33:33 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[culture]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[firing]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[management]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=840</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Being brave and thoughtful when letting people go includes encouraging them to engage you. I remember the first job I had where I had responsibility for hiring and firing. I was young and inexperienced, promoted beyond the point I was &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/the-final-cut/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/the-final-cut/">The Final Cut</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="The Final Cut" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/FinalCut_300.jpg" alt="Phone" /><br />
<figcaption>Being brave and thoughtful when letting people go includes encouraging them to engage you.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>I remember the first job I had where I had responsibility for hiring and firing. I was young and inexperienced, promoted beyond the point I was properly trained for. What I quickly found was that letting go younger or more junior people was easy, but letting go older and very senior people was difficult. I distinctly remember one person in particular: letting him go was a decision made by three of us at the executive level, and I chose to not participate in telling him, then more-or-less hiding while he packed up his things and left. It is among the most cowardly things I’ve ever done.</p>
<p>Letting people go is difficult. There is no getting around that. However, particularly as the person who made or contributed to the decision, you owe it to the person to have the courage to engage them and stretch yourself in the process. After all, no matter how much they may have deserved to be let go, no matter how much they may have made your life more difficult, from a power dynamics perspective you are the “winner”. You remain in the soft embrace of your employer, with paychecks continuing to roll in. They are being cast out into an uncertain and likely scary unknown that could have major repercussions on people who rely on them, too. It is thus incumbent upon you to stretch yourself in that termination process.</p>
<p>Now, with more experience and wisdom, I always engage deeply into the process of letting someone go. If it is appropriate, I want to be in the meeting where they are let go. At the very least, I am going to engage them that same day and give them an opportunity to ask me questions, or vent, or just talk about it. They are going to know they have an open door to talk during the “dead man walking” period, or anytime after. And, on their last day, I’m going to shake their hand and thank them for something they did for us that was good. It models how I want other employees to act, how I want our organization to behave, and treats the soon-departing in the best possible way.</p>
<p>They say the final cut is the cruelest. Surely, it does not need to be. By taking responsibility, being brave and treating people with consideration and respect it can be the honorable end to one thing and, hopefully, lead to something better for both sides.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/01/the-final-cut/">The Final Cut</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
